# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bwf-para-badminton-world-championships
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bwf-para-badminton-world-championships/2003-ibad-para-badminton-world-championships] The **2003 IBAD Para-Badminton World Championships** were held from 5 to 8 June 2003 in Cardiff, Wales.
[src:bwf-para-badminton-world-championships/2003-ibad-para-badminton-world-championships] 12 events were contested in the tournament.
[src:bwf-para-badminton-world-championships/2003-ibad-para-badminton-world-championships] Cardiff was chosen as the host city for the tournament in May 2003.
[src:bwf-para-badminton-world-championships/2003-ibad-para-badminton-world-championships] The Welsh Institute of Sport was chosen as the venue for the tournament.
[src:bwf-para-badminton-world-championships/2005-ibad-para-badminton-world-championships] The **2005 IBAD Para-Badminton World Championships** (Chinese: 2005年世界殘障羽球錦標賽) were held from 27 October to 1 November 2005 in Hsinchu, Taiwan.
[src:bwf-para-badminton-world-championships/2005-ibad-para-badminton-world-championships] 19 events were contested in the tournament.
[src:bwf-para-badminton-world-championships/2005-ibad-para-badminton-world-championships] 10 teams took part in the standing team event.
[src:bwf-para-badminton-world-championships/2005-ibad-para-badminton-world-championships] Malaysia won the event by defeating Chinese Taipei 2–1 in the final.
[src:bwf-para-badminton-world-championships/2007-ibad-para-badminton-world-championships] The **2007 IBAD Para-Badminton World Championships** (Thai: แบดมินตันคนพิการชิงแชมป์โลก 2007) were held from 27 October to 3 November 2007 in Bangkok, Thailand.
[src:bwf-para-badminton-world-championships/2007-ibad-para-badminton-world-championships] 24 events were contested in the tournament.
[src:bwf-para-badminton-world-championships/2007-ibad-para-badminton-world-championships] Bangkok was chosen as the host city for the tournament in April 2007.
[src:bwf-para-badminton-world-championships/2007-ibad-para-badminton-world-championships] Gymnasium 1, located inside the Bangkok Youth Center was selected as the venue for the tournament.
[src:bwf-para-badminton-world-championships/2007-ibad-para-badminton-world-championships] 11 teams took part in the standing team event.
[src:bwf-para-badminton-world-championships/2007-ibad-para-badminton-world-championships] Malaysia won the event by defeating Hong Kong 2–1 in the final.
[src:bwf-para-badminton-world-championships/2009-ibad-para-badminton-world-championships] The **2009 IBAD Para-Badminton World Championships** (Korean: 2009 세계장애인배드민턴선수권대회) were held from 7 to 12 September 2009 at the Olympic Fencing Stadium in Seoul, South Korea.
[src:bwf-para-badminton-world-championships/2009-ibad-para-badminton-world-championships] 22 events were contested in the tournament.
[src:bwf-para-badminton-world-championships/2009-ibad-para-badminton-world-championships] South Korea was chosen as the host for the Para-Badminton World Championships in August 2009, with Seoul being the host city of the tournament.
[src:bwf-para-badminton-world-championships/2009-ibad-para-badminton-world-championships] The Olympic Fencing Stadium in Bangi-dong was chosen as the venue for the tournament.
[src:bwf-para-badminton-world-championships/2009-ibad-para-badminton-world-championships] Seven teams competed in the standing team event.
[src:bwf-para-badminton-world-championships/2009-ibad-para-badminton-world-championships] Hong Kong received a bye in the quarter-finals.
[src:bwf-para-badminton-world-championships/2011-bwf-para-badminton-world-championships] The **2011 BWF Para-Badminton World Championships** (Spanish: *Campeonato Mundial de Parabádminton 2011*) were held from 22 to 26 November 2011 in Guatemala City, Guatemala.
[src:bwf-para-badminton-world-championships/2011-bwf-para-badminton-world-championships] 21 events were contested in the tournament.
[src:bwf-para-badminton-world-championships/2011-bwf-para-badminton-world-championships] This was also the last tournament to host the mixed team event, which was later discontinued in 2013.
[src:bwf-para-badminton-world-championships/2011-bwf-para-badminton-world-championships] In October 2011, the Badminton World Federation awarded Guatemala the rights to host the 8th Para-Badminton World Championships, with Guatemala City chosen as the host city of the tournament.
[src:bwf-para-badminton-world-championships/2011-bwf-para-badminton-world-championships] The team event of the Para-Badminton World Championships took place on 22 November 2011.
[src:bwf-para-badminton-world-championships/2011-bwf-para-badminton-world-championships] The event was created specifically for players that are competing in the standing events, ranging from STL2 to STU5.
[src:bwf-para-badminton-world-championships/2011-bwf-para-badminton-world-championships] Chinese Taipei received a bye in the quarter-final stage.
[src:bwf-para-badminton-world-championships/2019-bwf-para-badminton-world-championships] The **2019 BWF Para-Badminton World Championships** was held from 20 to 25 August 2019 in Basel, Switzerland.
[src:bwf-para-badminton-world-championships/2019-bwf-para-badminton-world-championships] After Basel was selected to be the host of 2019 BWF World Championships in March 2019, the organizing team proposed to hold the able-bodied badminton world championships together the para-badminton world championships.
[src:bwf-para-badminton-world-championships/2019-bwf-para-badminton-world-championships] The proposal was approved by Badminton World Federation thus marking the first time Para-Badminton World Championships is held together with World Badminton Championships in the same venue.
[src:bwf-para-badminton-world-championships/2019-bwf-para-badminton-world-championships] 313 players from 49 countries took part.
[src:bwf-para-badminton-world-championships/2022-bwf-para-badminton-world-championships] The **2022 BWF Para-Badminton World Championships** (officially known as the **Hulic Daihatsu BWF Para Badminton World Championships 2022** for sponsorship reasons) was held from November 1 to 6, 2022.
[src:bwf-para-badminton-world-championships/2022-bwf-para-badminton-world-championships] It was previously due to be held from October 25 to 31, 2021 in Tokyo, Japan.
[src:bwf-para-badminton-world-championships/2022-bwf-para-badminton-world-championships] On September 9, however, BWF announced that the tournament was postponed.
[src:bwf-para-badminton-world-championships/bwf-para-badminton-world-championships] The **BWF Para-Badminton World Championships** (formerly known as the **IBAD Para-Badminton World Championships**) is a badminton tournament organised by the Badminton World Federation.
[src:bwf-para-badminton-world-championships/bwf-para-badminton-world-championships] It's the most prestigious badminton competition, offering the most ranking points, along with the Summer Paralympics badminton events introduced in 2020.
[src:bwf-para-badminton-world-championships/bwf-para-badminton-world-championships] The highest ranked para-badminton players compete in six sport classes in five categories.
[src:bwf-para-badminton-world-championships/bwf-para-badminton-world-championships] The championships were organised under the Para Badminton World Federation (PBWF) before it merged with the BWF in June 2011.
